      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the search results for the paper **\"Understanding Deep Learning Requires Rethinking Generalization\"** by Zhang, Bengio, Hardt, Recht, and Vinyals (ICLR 2017):\n\n---\n\n## Paper Overview\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The paper is authored by Chiyuan Zhang, Samy Bengio, Moritz Hardt, Benjamin Recht, and Oriol Vinyals."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " It was published at ICLR 2017, and "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "was one of the three papers awarded the Best Paper Award at ICLR 2017."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- **arXiv**: [https://arxiv.org/abs/1611.03530](https://arxiv.org/abs/1611.03530)\n- **OpenReview**: [https://openreview.net/forum?id=Sy8gdB9xx](https://openreview.net/forum?id=Sy8gdB9xx)\n- **DBLP**: [https://dblp.org/rec/conf/iclr/ZhangBHRV17.html](https://dblp.org/rec/conf/iclr/ZhangBHRV17.html)\n- **Google Research**: [https://research.google/pubs/understanding-deep-learning-requires-rethinking-generalization/](https://research.google/pubs/understanding-deep-learning-requires-rethinking-generalization/)\n\n## Key Findings\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Despite their massive size, successful deep artificial neural networks can exhibit a remarkably small difference between training and test performance. Conventional wisdom attributes small generalization error either to properties of the model family, or to the regularization techniques used during training."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Through extensive systematic experiments, the authors show how these traditional approaches fail to explain why large neural networks generalize well in practice. Specifically, their experiments establish that state-of-the-art convolutional networks for image classification trained with stochastic gradient methods easily fit a random labeling of the training data."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "This phenomenon is qualitatively unaffected by explicit regularization, and occurs even if we replace the true images by completely unstructured random noise."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n## Additional Insights\n\n- **On implicit regularization**: "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "While explicit regularizers like dropout and weight-decay may not be essential for generalization, in neural networks we almost always choose our model as the output of running stochastic gradient descent. Appealing to linear models, the authors analyze how SGD acts as an implicit regularizer — for linear models, SGD always converges to a solution with small norm, hence the algorithm itself is implicitly regularizing the solution."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n- **On finite sample expressivity**: "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Even depth-2 networks of linear size can already represent any labeling of the training data."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\nA later expanded version was also published in *Communications of the ACM* as **\"Understanding deep learning (still) requires rethinking generalization\"** ([ACM link](https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3446776))."
      }
